fix(login): close encrypt-at-rest red-team findings (verification round 1)

Verification of the encrypt-at-rest login feature surfaced concrete bugs;
fixed and converted the repros into regression guards. 69 tests green,
typecheck + build + xvfb boot clean.

Findings fixed:
- A (data loss): disable path zeroized the DEK while a concurrent write
  could still re-encrypt, orphaning a file with no recoverable key. Added a
  directional `disabling` flag to the vault; secure-fs now consults
  shouldEncrypt() so a write racing decryptAll()->removeAuth() stays
  plaintext. Both migrations pause the reminder ticker (isMigrating()).
- B (plaintext leak): an orphaned *.tmp (crash debris) survived enable as
  cleartext because the encrypt sweep skips transient files. encryptAll now
  purges orphan temps first (cleanupOrphanTemps).
- isEncryptedFile always returned false: the 8-byte magic probe could never
  satisfy isEncrypted's 36-byte full-envelope length test, so the positional
  attachment readers served CIPHERTEXT for every encrypted attachment.
  Added vault.hasMagicPrefix() for the probe.
- 1 (silent failure): attachment readers masked locked/decrypt-fail as a
  generic read-error. secure-fs now tags throws EVAULTLOCKED/EDECRYPT;
  readAttachmentText/Bytes classify into reason locked|decrypt-failed.
- 2 (silent failure): bio-image readers masked locked/decrypt-fail as
  "no image". readOriginalDataUri surfaces it; thumbDataUri re-throws real
  faults but stays lenient on a missing (regenerable) thumb.
- Q4 (silent partial import): importCase swallowed a registry-write failure
  as "malformed bundle"; now only parse/shape errors are tolerated.

C (random 96-bit GCM IV, no global counter) reviewed: accepted/documented
limitation for single-user data volumes.

